The Arroyo

A dry canyon carved by a river that no longer flows, the Arroyo is a
jurisdictional wound in stone: part flood channel, part legal ruin,
part funerary machine. Long before the present desert routes hardened
into law, this branch of the Iseth watershed carried violent seasonal
floodwater toward the Deepwell Confluence basin. When drought cycles
intensified, the channel was first engineered, then taxed, then
abandoned, then repurposed.

The critical transformation was institutional. The Arroyo became a
place where water volume was translated into legal obligation.
Travelers were measured, assessed, and recorded. Debts were written
against drought. Oaths were notarized against thirst.

Five historical layers remain active simultaneously. Keeper-era
measurement: thirst oaths, silt tallies, and witness stones that
recorded both distance and water debt. Salt Ledger extraction:
toll courts carved into cutbanks, confiscation vaults, and mortuary
intake rooms for those who died in arrears -- "unpaid names" whose
funerary rites were withheld pending debt settlement. Pyramid
jurisdiction: Moon-descending legal language that reframed debt
default as spiritual trespass, creating a textual palimpsest of
Keeper numerics under Ledger seals under Moon clauses. Synod
coercion: simplified toll liturgy where "authorized thirst" became
both prayer and threat. And ecological takeover: scorpion colonies
nesting through ossuary chambers, embedding chitin and resin in old
record halls.

Four modern powers contest the canyon. Charter Reclaimers -- synod-
descended militants running extortion checkpoints with copied charter
rods. Dustbound Court-Dead -- former assessors and oath witnesses
raised by layered rite residue, demanding declarations and escorting
intruders to judgment points. The Brood of the Resin Matriarch --
canyon-adapted mega-scorpions centered in warm seep zones. And
Fault Manifestations -- dust vortices with voice-like harmonics,
ash figures holding impossible postures, and magnetic grit storms
aligned to old survey marks.

The canyon walls are a record written in overwritten inscriptions.
One regime carves atop another. No modern faction fully understands
all layers, but all claim legitimacy from them. The stone remembers
every court that sat here, and every court that failed.

