The Arroyo -- Trade Syndic Comparative Law File

The Arroyo is a dry canyon in the distant eastern desert. The Trade
Syndics maintain a file on it as a jurisdictional case study --
because it demonstrates what happens when you build law atop law
without clearing the foundations.

Five historical layers remain active simultaneously. Keeper-era
measurement: thirst oaths, silt tallies, witness stones. Salt
Ledger extraction: toll courts, confiscation vaults, mortuary intake
for those who died in arrears -- "unpaid names" whose rites were
withheld pending debt settlement. Pyramid jurisdiction reframing
debt default as spiritual trespass. Synod coercion where
authorized thirst became prayer and threat. And ecological
takeover: scorpions nesting through ossuary chambers.

Each regime carved atop the previous inscriptions. No regime cleared
the stone first. Law atop law atop law, with no foundation
visible.

The Syndics draw three lessons for Kiess governance.

First: the unpaid name precedent. The Salt Ledger Kingdoms
withheld burial from debtors -- the same mechanism as Midgaard's
deferred names. Obligation sealed against the dead, accumulating
without expiration. Kiess prohibits this explicitly. A debt dies
with the debtor unless a living party assumes it by witnessed
compact. No warrant against the voiceless.

Second: the palimpsest problem. When Kiess inherited Evermeet's
foundations, Three-Power Governance deliberately acknowledged the
old city through memorial waystones but built new law on cleared
ground. Evermeet's ordinances were read, recorded, and formally
extinguished. The Arroyo shows what happens when you skip that
step -- ambiguity compounds into chaos.

Third: the ecological warning. The canyon's oldest infrastructure
is now infested. Scorpion broods in assessment chambers. Resin in
record halls. When institutions abandon space, the space does not
stay neutral. Wall Command applies this to our northern perimeter:
every bell-post lost to the mist becomes hostile territory.

The Dustbound Court-Dead -- former assessors still demanding
declarations -- are process outliving purpose. The canyon remembers
every court that sat there, and every court that failed.

The Prism records: clear your foundations or your foundations will
bury you. The Arroyo carved that lesson in stone five times over,
and no one who carved it could read what came before.
